<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Fiona Mcneill (WSC026)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Fiona Mcn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ill (WSC026)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I work as a part-time academic.  I have had two maternity leaves and have worked part-time for several years.  The views expressed below reflect my personal thoughts on how my career has been able to flourish despite circumstances that lead to many women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dropping out of STEM careers.  I believe I have been lucky in several ways, and am unsure if my career would still be on track - and would almost certainly be less successful - if I had not been.  If the system were set up differently, I would have been le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ss reliant on luck, and other women in my position would have a better chance of continuing successfully in their careers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It was essential to me to have a partner who was willing and able to be flexible and fully involved with childcare, including doing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">extra childcare when I had to travel or had meetings outside of my normal work hours and sharing unexpected and one-off occurrences like child illness and school events.  I happened to be lucky to have a partner who had a flexible job, but institutions and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the government can make this possible for more women by:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:0.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cultivating an ethos within organisations that accepts that men are responsible for childcare as much as women, and hence are:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.81pt; padding-left:2.19pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equally open to applications for part-time and flexible work by men as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by women</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equally accommodating for men as women when time has to be taken off for emergency childcare</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equally open to men to taking time off after children are born as to women</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For the government, introducing legislation so that parental leave (rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> just maternity leave) is more balanced, with either partner having an equal right to it and - ideally - the full amount of parental leave only obtainable if both partners take at least some of it.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women will never have an equal chance of career developmen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t whilst childcare is seen primarily as a female issue.  Legislation and attitude-change has focussed on allowing women to balance work and childcare, which is certainly helpful to some women, but whilst this is seen as a balance that only women must find,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women’s careers will be much more fragile (because of the compromises made) and women will therefore be much more likely to drop out of their careers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It was extremely helpful to me to have colleagues who were accommodating when I needed to balance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">childcare and working because of working outside my normal hours - for example, bringing babies to meetings.  People were also accommodating when I had to take my babies to conferences whilst I was still breastfeeding, although I did not get any financial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or babysitting support to help with this.  Bringing in my tangible support so that mothers can travel for work whilst they are breastfeeding would be very helpful.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>